# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1845-to-1868-in-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the years 1845 to 1868 throughout the world.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At its December 1868 annual meeting, the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP) permitted professional clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twelve existing members did "go pro" and constitute the professional field for 1869.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1868 season records for 98 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 15 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors" (not marked), all of the 1869 "pros" (*), all 14 member clubs with at least twelve wins on record, and a few others.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the seven listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] At least four Association clubs not listed here would someday try professionalism: Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio (1870); Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana (1871); Middletown of Mansfield, Connecticut (1872); Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey (1873).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Meanwhile, only two brand new professional baseball clubs would be established in the next three years, the Chicago White Stockings for 1870 and the Boston Red Stockings for 1871.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Their commercial origins may be related to their survival alone by 1877, and on to 2010, while all of their rivals with older and amateur roots fell away.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1867 season records for 89 teams, many of them incomplete ("(inc)" in the table).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 17 of that season's teams "major" (not marked).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 13 member clubs with at least fourteen wins on record, and a few others.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the nine listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks ten clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Excelsior of Chicago and Buckeye of Cincinnati are listed because they were probably the strongest teams in the west after the Cincinnati Red Stockings.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Marshall Wright publishes 1866 season records for 58 of 93 association members, said to be complete for games between two member clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 20 of that season's teams "major" including three old New York rivals of the Knickerbockers.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] This table covers all of those "majors", all 14 members with at least eight wins on record, and a few others.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the fifteen listed clubs in Greater New York, no city is named in the first column; the comment gives their locales.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Star (*) marks eight clubs among twelve who would go pro in 1869, three seasons later.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] For the preceding 1865 season Marshall Wright lists 30 members with supposedly complete records for most of them.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Twenty-two of the thirty were in Greater New York.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek calls 19 teams "major" in the first season that he covers: sixteen of the members and three others (Lowell, Harvard, and Camden).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] No one traveled much and membership was still depressed by the Civil War.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] There had been 59 delegates at the March 1860 annual meeting, and 55 at the next annual meeting that December (on a new baseball calendar), who thereby intended to play during the 1861 season that the war curtailed.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1845-to-1868-in-baseball] Nine of 59 and eleven of 55 were from outside Greater New York.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The **1857 baseball convention** was a meeting of members from 16 New York City-area baseball clubs that took place over multiple sessions in early 1857.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] It passed numerous clarifications of the pre-existing Knickerbocker Rules and modifications that helped lead to the modern format of baseball games.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Among the items formalized were the length of games and the distance between bases.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] At the convention, multiple members of the New York Knickerbockers club presented the "Laws of Base Ball", a series of documents that contained proposed rules, some of which were edited in response to feedback.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The law documents drafted for the convention survived and were sold at auction for more than $3 million in 2016.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] After the pioneering New York Knickerbockers club was founded in 1845, baseball grew slowly at first in the New York City area.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] However, by 1855 it had started to accelerate in popularity, as two dozen teams were in existence that year.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The nature of games played between the teams changed during the period.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] While early Knickerbockers games functioned mainly as social events that allowed players to exercise and fraternize with other players, by 1855, competitive match games had grown more frequent.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] As a result, the existing rules proved inadequate in addressing various situations that arose in competitive play.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] While opposing teams agreed upon their own match rules, which led to changes in common practices, a uniform code of regulations was lacking.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Even items such as the types of balls and bats to be used were not standardized.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The rules also had aspects that could be taken advantage of in unintended ways that went against the spirit of the game.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Meanwhile, new clubs often wrote into sports columns in newspapers asking for clarifications on rules.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Another factor driving the push was the general improvement of fielding skills, which at the time was the most crucial aspect of the game.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The original Knickerbocker Rules, which the Knickerbockers used for internal play, dated back to 1845, with small adjustments made three years later.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Following an 1854 meeting involving three teams—the Eagles, Gothams, and Knickerbockers—a set of match play guidelines were coded to address rules differences between the clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] One year later, with the increase in match play accelerating, the idea of a convention addressing the rules was floated, but the Knickerbockers were not involved in the efforts, which proved futile.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] By 1856, the Knickerbockers were ready to participate, and in December of that year a call for a convention was made.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers took the lead in organizing the convention, as the team held an internal meeting on December 6, 1856.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] It formed a three-man committee led by Doc Adams to accomplish the task of gaining attendance from New York City-area clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Sixteen clubs agreed to participate in the convention, which was held over at least two sessions.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The first took place on January 22, 1857, while the second was held about a month later, on February 25.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Press advertisements indicated that a session would be held on February 3, but no records of any committee activities having taken place on that date are known to exist.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Of the 16 clubs, 14 sent representatives to the first meeting.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The other two teams sent members to the second session, but not all representatives from the first session returned.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] As a result, neither session had attendance from every team.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] At the January 22 meeting of the convention, which was held in a Broome Street hotel, each of the 14 attending clubs sent three delegates.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The teams started by naming officers; Adams was selected as president.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] A handful of other officers from varying teams were named.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The convention saw the Knickerbockers present a series of documents collectively titled the "Laws of Base Ball", which had been drafted in 1856.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Adams probably wrote one of the documents himself, according to historian John Thorn, while fellow Knickerbocker William Grenelle contributed a second Laws paper and a document titled "Rules for Match Games of Base Ball", which contained playing ground guidelines not addressed elsewhere.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The papers were then edited and put together prior to the convention.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Some of the papers Grenelle contributed have visible penciled changes, from a different writer; Thorn believes that Adams made the edits.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers did not initially gain approval for the drafts; instead, a rules committee was appointed to meet on January 28; the attending clubs each sent one delegate.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Other items discussed at the first meeting included the possibility of a baseball field being built in Central Park, which led to the appointment of a five-member lobbying committee, and the delegates voted to charge clubs a $2 assessment.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] When the rules committee met on January 28, William H.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Van Cott, a member of the Gothams, was named chairman.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers' proposal was discussed, and a final draft was made to present during the second full meeting of the committee.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Some of the items were amended after floor motions, but the resulting version was ultimately approved.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] One of the major items addressed in the Laws was the prescribed length of games.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Under the Knickerbocker Rules, games did not have a set number of innings, instead concluding when a team reached 21 runs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] This method left potential issues regarding match play, as was evidenced by an 1856 game between the Knickerbockers and the Empire club; each team scored 21 runs over eight innings and the game ended in a tie.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] This was not the only factor that threatened to prevent matches from having winners.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] As match play became more widespread in the mid-1850s, teams improved and contests became closer and lower-scoring in nature.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Under practices of the time, in the event that neither team scored 21 runs before darkness or inclement weather forced a stoppage of play, a game ended in a draw.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Teams seeking to play for a stalemate could easily do so by not swinging at pitches, as no system of calling balls and strikes existed.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The "Match Games" document originally indicated that games should last 12 innings, but the number was changed to nine during editing.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The issue resulted in a divide between the Knickerbockers and club delegates Adams and Louis Wadsworth; the team had supported seven-inning games, but Adams and Wadsworth sought longer contests.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Although *Porter*'s stated that the shorter game length had won support at the convention, nine-inning games were decided upon, following a motion by Wadsworth.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Also in the rules was a provision that, should a game be suspended due to weather, the leading team would be declared the winner if five innings had been played; these new rules served to remove the possibility of draws.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The convention also brought clarity to the topic of the distance between bases.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Previously, the distance had been listed as 42 paces between first base and third base, and from second base to home plate.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The actual distance depended upon the definition of "pace"; a two-and-a-half foot pace would have resulted in a distance of around 75 feet, while a person actually pacing out the steps could lead to inconsistencies.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Adams later wrote that the pre-existing standard "was rather vague".
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In the Rules document, he and Grenelle changed the definition of a baseball field to focus on the overall basepath.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The first page of Rules prescribed a 42-yard distance between first and third bases, and second base and home plate, which would have resulted in bases being 89.1 feet apart.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Before the convention, a change was made that Thorn called "a small step, but one of simple genius".
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The distance between bases was set at 90 feet, leaving 127 feet between second base and home plate.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In the Laws document, Adams also took a step to provide more precise specifications for how far the pitcher would stand from home plate.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] While the laws originally called for a distance of 15 to 16 yards, depending on where the pitcher decided to stand, he changed the document to set the distance at 45 feet.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Dating back to 1854, the previous regulations had merely called for the pitcher to be "not less than fifteen paces" from home plate, leaving open the possibility of pitchers positioning themselves off-center when throwing.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] To restrict the possible location, section 5 of the rules specified that the position be inside "a line four yard in length, drawn at right angles to a line from home to the second base, having a center upon that line".
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] As had been the case in 1845 rules, the document provided that balks could be called against pitchers, subject to the judgement of umpires, which would result in all baserunners moving up one base.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] One field regulation likely added due to input from the convention floor was a regulation restricting where batters could stand.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] It prevented batters from standing behind home plate; had the committee's draft not been tweaked, weakly hit balls would have had a greater chance of being foul balls.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Early baseball bats could be either round or flat.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Section 2 of the Laws document mandated the use of round bats, which were to be made of wood and limited to a maximum diameter of two inches.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers' original draft had permitted one side of the bat to be shaved flat in a manner similar to a cricket bat, which according to the document was meant to allow for improved aiming on batted balls.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] For unknown reasons, this part of the draft failed to make it through the rules committee.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The rules also addressed the size of the baseball, calling for balls to be between 6 and 6.5 ounces in weight, and between 10 and 10.25 inches in circumference.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Both sets of numbers were increased from the 1854 rules, although balls meeting the older guidelines ended up closer to modern equivalents.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] A surge in interest from gamblers, as well as the existence of loopholes for clubs to take advantage of existing player eligibility regulations, led to responses in the 1857 rules.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] A new addition in the Laws documents, in section 30, was a ban on gambling by players or umpires.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] This served to discourage gambling by involved parties, although fan wagers were not mentioned in the guideline.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] However, section 33 banned bystanders from talking with players or umpires during play, unless by request of an umpire.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In addition, the rules stated that players were required to be members of their clubs for 30 days before appearing in a game, and that they could play for only one team.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] These changes were made to avert a repeat of an 1856 game between the Gothams and Knickerbockers in which the Gothams had fielded a player who was a member of the Union Club at the same time, leading to protests by the Knickerbockers and criticism from the Union Club.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The customs of the day favored teams fielding nine-player squads in match games, although it was not specifically prescribed in existing rules and some games played outside the New York City area saw varying numbers of players.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Section 27 of the Laws codified the nine-player guideline, going against the wishes of the Knickerbockers, who had wanted the minimum player number set at seven.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Along with player and inning numbers, another item supported by the Knickerbockers that failed to make it past the rules committee was the "fly game", in which fielders who caught a batted ball on the fly would record an out, but not those who made a catch after the first bounce.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Under regulations of the time, an out was posted when a batted ball was caught after one bounce; this was known as the bound rule.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Adams himself was a strong proponent of the proposal.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The Knickerbockers proposed a compromise in which the fly game would apply to fair balls, but foul balls could be caught on a hop.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The committee rejected the proposal, leaving the bound game intact.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Newer clubs opposed the change due to a fear that fielders would wind up with hand injuries.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] They were joined by some established teams, as neither the Eagles nor Gotham backed the change.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] As part of the rules passed, baserunners were prohibited from advancing on balls caught on the fly; modern guidelines that allowed runners to tag up were not introduced until 1859.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] *Porter*'s had endorsed adding a regulation that would allow umpires to call strikes on batters "who did not swing at good pitches", but this also failed to gain a consensus.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The distance from the pitcher to home plate was extended two times after 1857; the second adjustment came in 1893.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In March 1858, yet another meeting of clubs was held.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] There, as Adams wrote, "the annual convention was declared a permanent organization, and with the requisite constitution and by-laws", the National Association of Base Ball Players was formed.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] That year, another significant change was made to the rules, as called strikes were added.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The adjustment, along with the addition of called balls in 1863, made the pitcher a more significant factor than in previous years.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The fly game was debated for another seven years after 1857 before a one-year trial was adopted in 1864 for balls hit in fair territory.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] The rule, which was expanded to cover foul balls in 1883, remains in use in modern baseball.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Twenty-three pages from the "Laws" draft documents survived, having been kept by Grenelle's family.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In 1999, they were sold to Frank Murray as part of a lot of vintage documents for $12,650.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] At the time, the authorship was not known.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In 2015, Murray came forward to SCP Auctions, and analysis revealed the documents' authorship and significance.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] At an online auction the following year, the documents sold to Hayden Trubitt for over $3.2 million, the most that baseball-related papers had ever gone for at the time and more than three times what the auction house had estimated.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] In 2018-2019, the Laws appeared in a Library of Congress exhibition, having been loaned by Trubitt.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1857-baseball-convention] Since May 2026, by virtue of a long-term loan from Trubitt, the documents have been on display at the National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum in Cooperstown, New York as part of the museum's "Rules of Base Ball" exhibit.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The **1858 Brooklyn–New York all-star game**, sometimes known as the "**Great Base Ball Match of 1858**", was a series of baseball contests between select standout players of from various amateur clubs in Manhattan and Brooklyn during the summer of 1858.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] In inviting only select players from multiple clubs, these games are now considered precursors to modern professional all-star games.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Hosted at the Fashion Course in Queens, the series is also noticeable for being the first baseball events to charge admission for spectators.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Brooklyn and New York faced off three times—on July 20, August 17, and September 10—with New York ultimately prevailing in the series, 2–1.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The number of amateur clubs in New York and Brooklyn grew from 6 in 1854 to about 24 the next year, with continued rapid expansion for the rest of the decade.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Sixteen New York–area clubs convened in 1857 to refine the standard rules, making fundamental decisions like setting the bases 90 feet apart.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] An outgrowth of this convention was the National Association of Base Ball Players (NABBP), the first baseball governing organization.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] In 1858, the NABBP decided to organize a series of games pitting the top players from New York and Brooklyn member clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Match organizers sought to find a neutral hosting ground easily accessible by public transit; they settled on the Fashion Course horse racing grounds in Flushing, Queens, which was reachable by omnibus, rail, and trolley.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The course featured a grandstand, enabling spectators to sit in comfort.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The organizers created an all-dirt infield on the course by stripping away grass turf; the costs associated with landscaping the field and renting the facility incurred unexpected costs for the clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] To cover these costs—and taking advantage of the gated entrances to the facility—the clubs decided to charge an admission fee of 10 cents for the event.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The 1858 matches thus became (in addition to being the first all-star games), the first to be played in an enclosed ground and the first to require paid admission.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The highly anticipated first match, on July 20, featured members of the Knickerbocker, Gotham, Eagle, Empire, Harlem, and Union clubs on the New York side, and members of the Atlantics, Excelsior, Putnam, and Eckford clubs from Brooklyn.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Among the New York players was Knickerbocker Harry Wright, who would be elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame nearly a century later.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Attendance estimates for this game range from 4,000–10,000.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The New York squad prevailed in the debut match, 22–18.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The game ball used in this match survives to this day and is in the possession of the Baseball Hall of Fame.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Both club managers made personnel changes after the first match.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Eckford of Brooklyn cofounder Frank Pidgeon was moved from shortstop to pitcher for this game.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Pidgeon's scorecard for the match survives today.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] The Brooklyn stars routed New York, 29–8, evening the series.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] After its strong showing in the second match, Brooklyn left its lineup mostly intact for the rubber match.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] New York, however, made major lineup changes, including a change at pitcher.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Longtime Knickerbocker and baseball pioneer Doc Adams served as umpire and was the first umpire to apply an NABBP rule that called batters out after non-swinging strikes.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Frank Pidegon returned as pitcher for Brooklyn, logging 438 pitches during the match.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] New York won, 29–18, handing them the series victory.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Although the clubs did not seek or retain the profits, they proved that baseball was popular enough to become a profitable venture.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] A number of 1858 all-stars, including Harry Wright and William H.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Van Cott, participated in the "first-ever multi-club intercity tournament" in 1862, competing against Philadelphia clubs.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Although New York won the series, Brooklyn clubs proved to dominate local competition in the 1860s.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] By 1862, Bill Cammeyer established the first enclosed ballpark designed solely for baseball use—Union Grounds in Williamsburg—and began charging regular admission fees.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] By the end of the 1860s, baseball was in the process of becoming a professional industry, and in 1871 the NABBP was replaced by the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players—the first professional baseball league.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1858-brooklyn-new-york-all-star-game] Major League Baseball played its first official all-star game in 1933.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1869 throughout the world.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] At its December 1868 meeting the NABBP permitted professional clubs for the first time.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] There had been no professional clubs outside the Association, and no brand new professional clubs were established for 1869.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Rather, the entire first-year effect of the change was that twelve existing members declared professional status.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] All of them had fielded at least regionally strong teams in 1868 and most if not all had compensated at least some of their players.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Cincinnati Red Stockings were first to sign an all-salary team, ten men for eight months.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] From the west, the strongest team in Cleveland also joined the pro field.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] From the eastern corridor there were ten including all of the one-time champions and claimants.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Otherwise the record of professional matches (see table) is remarkable for its balance, relative to the records of the stronger teams during the amateur era and to most of the following pro seasons.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Irvingtons did not travel, or win; after July they played only two matches with the Mutuals (four in all).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Forest City of Cleveland did not travel far, only to Cincinnati and upstate New York.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Those two did not face each other or any of the three teams standing just above them.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] That imbalance, typical of the time, contributed to the losing records of all five.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Weaker teams were weaker gate attractions with less incentive and almost always less ability to travel.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Irvingtons disbanded and the Keystones returned to amateur ranks, but all the others remained in the professional field for 1870.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Indeed, all but Cincinnati remained in operation at least to 1872.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The amateur ranks during 1869 probably included some clubs who compensated their players by traditional methods such as division of the gate receipts (as Spalding said of Rockford by the end of the decade).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Four of the amateurs would "go pro" in 1870, including the Forest City of Rockford, Illinois, with some success.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The professional field was relatively strong in 1869 and its weaker teams did not play many games.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Forest Citys did not beat any pro teams, but they played only four matches with Cincinnati, losing three by twenty runs and one by merely 14–15 on July 24.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] (They traveled no further than Detroit and Ohio while eastern pros also traveled no further than Ohio, home of their westernmost rivals.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Stars of Brooklyn, led by pitcher Candy Cummings, won 2 of 7 matches with pro teams, beating the Mutuals 26–12 on June 19 and the visiting Olympics of Washington 49–11 on July 19.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] They lost five to the Mutuals and Atlantics by only 28 runs, total margin.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Harvard college won 1 of 6 against pros, beating the powerful Athletics of Philadelphia 35–21 on July 9; the next day they lost a close one to the much weaker Keystones.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Against amateurs Star won fourteen with one defeat; Harvard won thirteen with one draw.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Next season they would win six each against the slightly larger pro field.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Lowell of Boston, listed among the major teams by Bill Ryczek, played three fairly close game against the pros, losing 21–26 to the Mutuals, 9–29 to undefeated Red Stockings, and 33–38 to the Eckfords.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Pastime of Baltimore won 2 of 9 against pro teams, including 1 of 4 local matches Maryland and one with the Troy Haymakers.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] The Olympics, Mutuals, Athletics, and Keystones beat them four teams by only 32 runs, total margin.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey beat Irvington 16–15 and lost twice to the Eckfords.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] These six amateur teams barely faced each other on the field: Lowell lost six to its local rival Harvard and one to Star (July 5, the Fourth being a Sunday that year).
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1869-in-baseball] Harvard toured for ten days but played only the professional Eckfords in New York City.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Ten of the twelve professional clubs from 1869 remained in that field for 1870, all except Keystone of Philadelphia and Irvington, New Jersey, from Greater New York.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The five newcomers were Union of Morrisania, now in New York City; Tri-Mountain of Boston; Riverside of Portsmouth, Ohio; Forest City of Rockford, Illinois; and the Chicago White Stockings, the only brand new club.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Union was a founding member from the 1857 convention and Forest City had been one of the strongest amateurs remaining in 1869.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The records of the teams in professional matches, ranked by wins (see table), reveal three groups of five with sharp outlines.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] A big group of thirteen and a little of group of two are equally clear, considering the numbers of defeats, pro matches, and all matches (not shown), and are supported by the subsequent history.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The two more ambitious newcomers played only a few pro matches and never returned to the professional field.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Mighty Cincinnati and venerable Union also shut down after this season.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] All the others joined the new professional association established that winter (NAPBBP), seven as founding members and four in 1872 or 1873.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The Mutuals, Athletics, and Chicago White Stockings survived to found the National League in 1876.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Four amateur teams defeated professionals more than once and two of them demonstrated that they were as strong as middling pros.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Harvard college fielded its strongest team, which toured nationally in the summer and won 6 of 16 against professional teams all season.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Star of Brooklyn, featuring Hall of Fame pitcher Candy Cummings, won 6 of 13 against pros.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Pastime of Baltimore won 4 of 24 including 1 of 4 with the Troy Haymakers, 1 of 2 with Olympic, and 2 of 5 with Maryland.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The Pastimes lost badly to Harvard and won one of three close matches with the Stars.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey won 2 of 8, both at the expense of venerable Eckford; the Resolutes remained in operation until a failed venture into the professional field in 1873.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Bill Ryczek lists Lowell of Boston and the Keystone of Philadelphia (pro in 1869) among the major teams.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] They did not defeat any professionals but showed strength comparable to Pastime, Resolute, and the weaker pros.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Considering the professionals in three groups of five ranked by wins in pro matches (see table), the stronger pros won 37 of 41 against the six amateur teams covered here; the middling pros won 13 of 18; the weaker pros won 6 of 15.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Here are the records of those amateurs against the pros.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] One of the elite professional teams, the Athletics of Philadelphia won eight matches with Harvard, Lowell, Keystone, and Pastime, with 20 to 34 runs scored and 11- to 22-run margins.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Three amateur clubs of 1870 would later enter the all-professional National Association for one season each: Kekionga of Fort Wayne, Indiana in 1871; Mansfield of Middletown, Connecticut in 1872; Resolute of Elizabeth, New Jersey in 1873.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] Harvard continued to field strong amateur teams, but amateurs would not again hold their own with middling pros.
[src:1845-to-1868-in-baseball/1870-in-baseball] The Stars won a championship in 1871 under the new all-amateur Association (NAABBP), before Candy Cummings joined the pros in 1872.
